At the marked line, you'll need to execute the `VirtualProtect` function, which is used to change the protection properties of a specified memory block to make it executable and readable. Here's how you can fill in that section:

```c
// VirtualProtect
RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rsp -= 8;
RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rip = (DWORD64)VirtualProtect;
RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rcx = (DWORD64)ImageBaseAddress;
RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rdx = Optional->SizeOfImage;
RopVirtualProtectExecute.R8 = PAGE_EXECUTE_READ;
RopVirtualProtectExecute.R9 = (DWORD64)&PreviousProtectionAttribute;
```

This section sets up the context for executing the `VirtualProtect` function:

- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rsp -= 8;`: Adjust the stack pointer to reserve space for return address.
- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rip = (DWORD64)VirtualProtect;`: Set the instruction pointer to the address of the `VirtualProtect` function.
- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rcx = (DWORD64)ImageBaseAddress;`: Set the first parameter (`lpAddress`) of `VirtualProtect` to the base address of the image.
- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.Rdx = Optional->SizeOfImage;`: Set the second parameter (`dwSize`) of `VirtualProtect` to the size of the image.
- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.R8 = PAGE_EXECUTE_READ;`: Set the third parameter (`flNewProtect`) of `VirtualProtect` to `PAGE_EXECUTE_READ` to make the memory block executable and readable.
- `RopVirtualProtectExecute.R9 = (DWORD64)&PreviousProtectionAttribute;`: Set the fourth parameter (`lpflOldProtect`) of `VirtualProtect` to the address of the variable storing the previous protection attribute.

With this setup, you're ready to call `VirtualProtect` with the specified parameters.

