To complete the `getLine` function, you need to implement the logic for reading a line from a file. You can achieve this by dynamically allocating memory for a buffer, reading characters from the file until you encounter a newline character (`'\n'`), and then returning the line.

Here's how you can implement the `getLine` function:

```c
char *getLine(FILE *f)
{
    int bufferSize = 128; // Initial buffer size
    char *buffer = (char *)malloc(bufferSize * sizeof(char));
    if (buffer == NULL) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Memory allocation failed\n");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    int index = 0;
    int ch;

    while ((ch = fgetc(f)) != EOF && ch != '\n') {
        buffer[index++] = (char)ch;
        if (index >= bufferSize) {
            bufferSize *= 2; // Double the buffer size if needed
            buffer = (char *)realloc(buffer, bufferSize * sizeof(char));
            if (buffer == NULL) {
                fprintf(stderr, "Memory reallocation failed\n");
                exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
            }
        }
    }

    if (index == 0 && ch == EOF) { // Handle empty file
        free(buffer);
        return NULL;
    }

    buffer[index] = '\0'; // Null-terminate the string
    return buffer;
}
```

This function reads characters from the file `f` until it encounters either the end of the file (`EOF`) or a newline character (`'\n'`). It dynamically reallocates memory for the buffer as needed to accommodate the entire line. Finally, it null-terminates the string and returns the dynamically allocated buffer containing the line read from the file.

